    {
      "check_id": "CWE-79",
      "path": "ui/src/template.html",
      "start": {
        "line": 3,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 3,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Potential Script Injection via Template Placeholder\n\nThe template.html file contains a `%%script%%` placeholder inside a `<script>` tag: `<script>%%script%%</script>`. If server-side code replaces this placeholder with user-controlled input without proper sanitization, it would allow arbitrary JavaScript injection. Since the content is placed directly inside a script block, no HTML encoding would prevent execution - the attacker's code would run as JavaScript directly.\n\nImpact: An attacker could inject arbitrary JavaScript code that executes in the context of the user's browser session, potentially stealing cookies, session tokens, PII data, or performing actions on behalf of the user.\n\nFix: Ensure that any data substituted into the %%script%% placeholder is strictly validated and never includes user-controlled input. If dynamic content must be inserted, use a proper Content Security Policy and ensure the substituted content is from a trusted, static source only.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-79"
          ],
          "finding_id": "da3e6981-51ac-45db-895c-ad85bcd59385"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-306",
      "path": "main.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 185,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 185,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Missing Authentication on GET /select endpoint - PII Exposure\n\nThe GET /select endpoint returns user records including PII (name, address, email, contact) and password hashes without any authentication check. Anyone can query for any user's data.\n\nImpact: Any unauthenticated user can access PII (names, addresses, emails, phone numbers) and password hashes of any user in the system.\n\nFix: Implement authentication middleware and require valid credentials before returning user data.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-306"
          ],
          "finding_id": "89bb75d8-fc46-4b52-91bc-7d6d8a6d63a3"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-200",
      "path": "main.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 143,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 143,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Sensitive Data Exposure - Password Hashes Returned in SQL Query Results\n\nThe `run_sql_query` function executes `SELECT *` queries and returns all columns including password hashes in the response. While the function maps named fields and skips index [3] (password) in the single-result case, the multi-result case at line 162 returns raw tuples including the password hash at index [3]. The /select endpoint with SQL injection can also return password hashes via `SELECT *`.\n\nImpact: Password hashes (MD5) are exposed to unauthenticated users through the API response, enabling offline password cracking.\n\nFix: Never return password hashes in API responses. Explicitly exclude the password column from SELECT queries or filter it from results before returning.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-200"
          ],
          "finding_id": "5f641445-767f-46d1-a052-4f8102e1ce46"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-312",
      "path": "main.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 207,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 207,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Password Hash Stored in NoSQL Database for User Registration\n\nWhen a new user is created via PUT /user, the MD5 password hash is stored in the NoSQL database along with other user data. The `get_nosql_users` function (line 172) attempts to pop 'password' from results, but this is a fragile defense-in-depth measure. The password hash is stored in cleartext-equivalent form (MD5) in the NoSQL store.\n\nImpact: MD5 password hashes stored in the NoSQL database can be easily reversed if the database is compromised.\n\nFix: Use a strong password hashing algorithm (bcrypt, argon2) and avoid storing password hashes in the NoSQL database if not needed for authentication.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-312"
          ],
          "finding_id": "3574cb4c-76fb-485e-984c-3e887ee05573"
        }
      }
    },
